290":"1290","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wace","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Wass  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wass","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Wace</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Waz(z)o</i>), a pet form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names beginning with <i>Wad-</i> (compare   Wade   1). The name <i>Wace</i> was common among the Normans, alongside the Parisian French variant <i>Gace</i>, and was latinized as <i>Wazo</i> (nominative), <i>Wazonis</i> (genitive).","English (of Norman origin): occasionally, perhaps a variant of   Vause   with vocalizing of initial <i>V-</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>was(se)</i> ‘sharp, cutting’."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From E